In late Dec 2022; a probably starved Cinereous Vulture was reported to Forest Officials in Khairagarh Town; close to the Forest Office only; in a field. The Bird rescued by villagers was in very bad condition and was immediately referred to Naya Raipur Jungle Safari under supervision of Vet Dr. Verma. The Bird at the time of rescue weighed somewhere close to 3.5 Kgs only and was not in condition to raise its head and was in critical condition. However the team at Naya Raipur Jungle Safari under the Forest Department took great care and the recovery phase started. ----In the first week of January 2023 and I along with Shri Mohit Sahu (Sr Birder, Member - State Wetland Authority of Chhattisgarh & Ex member CG Wildlife Board) visited the Jungle Safari on 11th January 2023 . On the same day we weighed the Bird and it was somewhere around 7.5 Kgs. Bird looked quite active and aggressive; and was feeding well on its own. No sign of injury or weakness reflected in its behavior as well. ----Based on above behavior and signs; we discussed its probable release and it was mutually decided with the Forest Department Team that Vulture be released in Khairagarh only near to the location where it was rescued. ----On 16th January morning we first ringed the bird with a Green Ring bearing no M63 (Photo of Ringed Bird attached for reference) and measurements were taken; bird's wing to wing measurement was approx 8 Ft and the bird was quite active & aggressive. Ring was made available by Mr. Sachin Ranade (BNHS Guwahati) and he guided me on how to ring the bird. The Vulture was then taken into a cage and we started for Khairagarh Town which is approximately 110 kms from Raipur City. ----The CCF Raipur (Madam Pronita Pal) along with Vet Team of Naya Raipur Jungle Safari along with Shri Mohit Sahu and myself went for the release and were joined by DFO Khairagarh and SDO and other Forest Officials. We went to the selected location so as to ensure that Vulture is released at the earliest.----At the time of release Vulture looked perfectly fit and showed no sign of fatigue or injury. Once released it took some time to adjust to the environment and took flight on its own within 15 minutes and perched on a nearby tree. After some time in presence of the Forest Team, Vulture took another flight of 100 meters and perched on top of a dead tree and remained there till evening. ----The Forest Department had ensured a volunteer (Mr. Pratik Thakur & Mr. Abhijeet Sharma) to keep watch on Vulture for next 2-3 days, and on 17th January 2023, Vulture was seen on the same perch in the morning; vulture during the day flew to the opposite cliff and remained there (an approx. flight of 500 mtrs). On 18th  January 2023, Vulture took a long flight towards Maharashtra State and was not seen afterwards. The information regarding release of Vulture was also communicated to nearby Villages through respective panchayats and messages delivered to active NGOs in Bhandara/Gondia Dist as well.

TRIP COMMENTS: Spectacular movement of raptors across the highway. It started with a group of vultures off to the southeast. They began to form small groups, then kettled together. There was also a dramatic lift off of vultures off to the north west. These may have been departing from a roost site, but probably had been feeding on a kill since we first spotted them at treetop level. Repeated and careful counts of all birds in the air at one time consistently produced totals between 90 and 100, not including the falcons, accipiters, and the smaller serpent-eagle. We photographed as many birds as possible when they were overhead. The birds that lifted off from the northwest never came overhead. In addition to the vultures that moved overhead in a northwesterly direction, a flock of alpine swifts moved in the same direction.

Started higher then yesterday and spent a lot of time with the Monals. 2500-2800m. -Found a carcass of a Sambar (or Tahr?) attended by Vultures,(at least 9 Himslayan, 1 young Black, a Lammergeier, 2LBCrows and a Steppe Eagle). The animal is not yet really opened and only the Vultures have started feeding.-Also a Pika!-Pxxx
